# WobbleBot — sample Caddyfile (HTTPS reverse proxy for cli/web)
#
# Caddy auto-provisions LetsEncrypt certificates and renews them.
# Pick ONE of the three blocks below depending on how you reach
# cli/web; delete the other two. The blocks are commented out so
# the file is safe to copy as-is.
#
# In all three cases, cli/web stays bound to 127.0.0.1:8000
# (its default). Caddy listens publicly + reverse-proxies to
# the loopback address. Operators do NOT need to expose
# cli/web's port to anything except Caddy.

# --------------------------------------------------------------- #
# Option A: Public domain (LetsEncrypt auto-cert)                #
# --------------------------------------------------------------- #
# Use when: you have a domain pointed at this host's public IP
# (e.g. wobblebot.your-domain.com via Cloudflare DNS A-record).
# Caddy will auto-provision a real cert via LetsEncrypt's HTTP-01
# challenge. Requires inbound port 80 + 443 reachable from the
# public internet for the cert renewal.
#
# Trade-off: anyone on the internet can REACH the login page
# (rate-limited + bcrypt-hashed, but still an attack surface).
# Pair with operator IP allowlist via the firewall, OR use the
# Tailscale option below instead.
#
# wobblebot.your-domain.com {
#     reverse_proxy 127.0.0.1:8000
#
#     # Recommended security headers for any web app handling
#     # operator-only credentials. HSTS pins HTTPS for a year;
#     # the others are belt-and-suspenders defaults.
#     header {
#         Strict-Transport-Security "max-age=31536000; includeSubDomains"
#         X-Content-Type-Options nosniff
#         X-Frame-Options DENY
#         Referrer-Policy strict-origin-when-cross-origin
#     }
# }


# --------------------------------------------------------------- #
# Option B: LAN-only (Caddy local CA, no public exposure)        #
# --------------------------------------------------------------- #
# Use when: you want HTTPS for LAN clients (your phone, a tablet,
# a second laptop) without exposing cli/web to the public
# internet. Caddy's internal CA mints a cert for the LAN IP or
# `.local` hostname. Browsers will warn on first visit until you
# trust Caddy's root CA on each client device (Caddy outputs
# instructions on first launch).
#
# Replace `192.168.1.42` with your host's actual LAN IP, or use
# a `.local` mDNS hostname if your network supports it.
#
# https://192.168.1.42 {
#     tls internal
#     reverse_proxy 127.0.0.1:8000
# }


# --------------------------------------------------------------- #
# Option C: Tailscale Serve / Funnel (recommended for solo ops)  #
# --------------------------------------------------------------- #
# Use when: you want remote access without managing certs or
# opening firewall ports. Tailscale provides a free MagicDNS
# hostname (e.g. wobblebot.your-tailnet.ts.net) + auto-cert via
# its built-in ACME integration.
#
# **No Caddy needed for this option** — Tailscale serves the
# reverse proxy itself. Use Tailscale's CLI directly:
#
#     # One-shot: expose cli/web on https://wobblebot.<tailnet>.ts.net
#     tailscale serve --https=443 --set-path=/ http://localhost:8000
#
# That's it. Tailscale handles cert + DNS. Only devices on your
# tailnet can reach cli/web. For broader access (still
# authenticated end-to-end by tailnet membership), use
# `tailscale funnel` instead of `tailscale serve`.
#
# Trade-off: locks you into Tailscale's account model. No
# self-hosted DNS; can't pre-share cert with non-Tailscale
# clients.
